Automated Reserves - BI v3 Implementation

Purpose of the Sweep Impact Analysis

The purpose of the sweep impact analysis is to evaluate the effect of transitioning from one model (BI v2) to another (BI v3) on outstanding reserve predictions. This process involves calculating the difference between the actual outstanding reserve in CIM (Claim Information Management), primarily driven by BI v2, and the predictions produced by BI v3.

The analysis also focuses on validating that:
	•	Predictions align with expected outcomes.
	•	The variables in CIM for each Reserve Line (RL) are consistent with those in the API post-implementation.

The following sections outline the steps to be taken in the sweep impact analysis, pre-sweep testing, data validation, and implementation testing, along with a structured procedure for efficient future use.

Procedure

1. IT Sweep Test and Pre-Sweep Analysis

Objective

The sweep impact is defined as the difference between the actual outstanding reserve in CIM for granular cases and the BI v3 model predictions. Initial testing will be conducted using a sample of 500 exposures, processed through the claim exception batch in the CC Perf region environment, to ensure process accuracy.

Steps

	1.	Coordination with IT:
	•	Contact IT to confirm availability for the sweep analysis, ensuring there are no competing priorities (e.g., code freezes or high-priority projects).
	•	Collaborative Testing: The IT team collaborates closely to ensure successful setup and execution of the sweep analysis.
	2.	Data Preparation:
	•	Extract Open Reserve Lines: Use a specified date to retrieve all open reserve lines along with relevant model variables. For the final sweep, ensure the data is as recent as possible (use pool 01 if needed).
	•	Reserve Line Selection: Choose reserve lines based on the automated reserve model, focusing on those affected by the change. For major model changes, use all open lines; for minor updates, use only impacted lines.
	3.	Test Sample (500 Exposures):
	•	Use a sample of 500 exposures as a testing subset. This sample helps simulate the process without impacting full-scale operations.
	•	Key Consideration: Some Reserve Lines (RLs) may not pass through the claim exception batch if they are closed or otherwise unavailable.

Purpose of the 500 Exposure Test

This initial sample helps identify potential discrepancies between CIM and the Claim Center by simulating a controlled sweep. This process assists in verifying model functionality and exposing gaps that need addressing.

Additional Tests

	•	Prediction Consistency Check: Confirm that predictions logged by the API are consistent with those in development.
	•	Variable Verification: Verify that the inputs from CIM match those recorded in the API logs. Any discrepancies should be investigated to identify potential impacts on model predictions.

2. Sweep Impact Report Generation

The following steps outline how to create a comprehensive sweep impact report, breaking down data validation, reserve prediction, and the final impact assessment.

2.1 Data Quality Validation

	1.	Validation Steps:
	•	Open Reserve Line Validation: Use a reporting tool (e.g., MicroStrategy) to confirm the count of open reserve lines.
	•	Input Consistency: Validate that the inputs from CIM match those in the API logs, ensuring uniformity across environments.
	•	Sweep Test in CC Perf Region: Conduct a sweep test in the CC Perf region with IT support to confirm data accuracy and readiness for full implementation.
	2.	Assignment and Timeline:
	•	A designated team member will be responsible for the data validation tasks, estimated to take up to three days.

2.2 Reserve Prediction

	1.	Predict Reserves: Use the new BI v3 model to predict reserves for the selected lines. This prediction provides a basis for comparing results against the actual outstanding reserve driven by BI v2.

2.3 Impact Calculation

	1.	Calculate Impact Difference:
	•	The impact is calculated by comparing the predicted reserves from BI v3 with the actual reserves from BI v2. Using the outstanding reserve as a baseline, this analysis will provide a clear understanding of the model change’s effects.
	2.	Generate Final Report:
	•	Report Template: Use the sweep_impact.html template available in the repository for consistency. This report should detail the impact split by key variables, such as policy product and location.
	•	Stakeholder Presentation: Format the report to meet stakeholder requirements, providing a breakdown by variables (e.g., policy product, loss location province).

2.4 Instructions for Future Report Enhancements

	1.	Improvement Note:
	•	Document areas for future improvement, such as refining the code in the sweep_impact.html template to capture additional variables or metrics as needed.

3. IT Test Instructions Before Deployment

The IT team is responsible for conducting a test sweep impact analysis before full deployment to ensure the environment is ready for BI v3 implementation.

Test Requirements

	1.	Environment: Tests will be conducted in the CC Perf region, which mirrors production-like data for accuracy.
	2.	Test Scope:
	•	Script Execution: A script will be run to add a list of exposures (provided by BI) to the claim exception batch.
	•	Support Availability: IT staff should be available to address any questions related to variable processing (e.g., how variables are sent to the API).

Estimated Time

	•	Script Creation: Approximately a couple of hours to prepare the script.
	•	Script Execution: About 10 minutes to run the script.

Validation Process

	1.	Add Exposures to Claim Exception Batch:
	•	Run the script to insert exposures into the batch and verify that they process without issues.
	2.	Prediction Verification:
	•	Confirm that the BI v3 predictions match expected values for all exposures.

4. Handling Issues in the Sweep Process

BI Team Responsibilities

	1.	Exposure List Management:
	•	Provide the list of exposures to be processed in the claim exception batch.
	•	Validation of Predictions: Ensure that the predictions generated for these exposures align with expected outcomes.

Issue Resolution

	1.	Discrepancy Resolution:
	•	If discrepancies arise between internal predictions and the sweep outcomes, adjust the variables sent to the model as needed.
	•	Implementation Timing: Determine whether fixes should occur before or after full deployment based on the impact of the issue.
	2.	IT Side:
	•	API Call Triggering: For exposures with open Automated reserves, trigger a call to R during the nightly claim exception batch.
	•	Flagging Mechanism: Use a script to set the lastreservecalculated_ext field on exposure to true for exposures provided by BI.
	•	Automatic Trigger: Once the field is set to true, the claim exception batch will automatically trigger a call to R.

Regular IT Testing

	1.	Objective:
	•	IT is expected to conduct regular tests during new model implementations to ensure that all processes function as expected.
	2.	Sweep Test Validation:
	•	Ensure IT successfully flags exposures when passing them through the claim exception batch.
	•	Closed Reserve Lines: Check logs to ensure that no exposures are excluded from processing due to closed statuses.

